The paper discusses building machine learning models to predict audiovisual quality directly from a set of correlated parameters. This involves using techniques such as Random Forests, Bagging, Deep Learning, and Genetic Programming. The paper also mentions using a dataset that reflects contemporary real-time configurations for video frame rate, video quantization, noise reduction parameters, and network packet loss rate. Based on this information, the most likely sub-categories are Multimedia (cs.MM), Information Theory (cs.IT), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV), and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE).
